Questions for you.<br>
<br>
From what point do you consider the US a country?  What year?<br>
<br>
When was the constitution written and put into effect?<br>
<br>
All I'm trying to point out to you with the confederated states example is that the EU currently is in a stage of development very similar to early US.  They have a very loose federation of culturally distinct and mostly autonomous regions tied together by a single political body without too many powers other than inter region dealings and some economic power.  Now, does this mean that they are not a single political body?  Did the US not qualify as a nation before the implementation of the constitution?  <br>
<br>
Currently, the EU is a mess of rules meant to contrain the central government and give the individual nations autonomy.  It's a rather ineffectual union without much real unity behind it.  That does not mean the basic idea behind it is not that of a single political unit.  In fact, a lot of the negative feelings towards it in Europe are generated because many Europeans feel like they are headed towards a 'United States of Europe'.<br>
<br>
here, your own quote<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Also, on your comment about the original confederated states, LMAO ..The states werent a confederation after the Constitution. They were confederate in first formation when they realized that didnt work. They then created our current, representative republic with a federalism model. Your history is flawed. It didnt just grow together.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
of course it didnt 'just' grow together.  It was put together by people who realized the flaws in the confederation.  However, do you consider the US not to have existed before the constitution was put into place?  Constitutional convention began in September of 1786.  Constitution itself was written and signed in 1787.  Do you believe that the US did not exist as a country before this?  Would you argue that celebrating the birth of the US in 1776 is a sham?<br>
<br>
And yes, I am well aware that the national guard is not an army for the individual states.  However, rather than go into personal attacks you may want to examine the origins or the national guard in more detail.  The fact that today's national guard is very different from what it was during the birth of the US is a good point, but as I said, the EU is in a very early stage of development compared to the US.<br>
<br>
As far as the economy and your argument that I am nitpicking details, here's your exact question:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> 2) Who is the number one economy in the world? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If you want to discuss GDP, you should have said so in the original question.  By all means, looking at current GDP, the US has the strogest economy in the world.  Please, detail what sort of answer you're looking for or dont get mad if people give answers other than the one you intend.  <br>
<br>
Obvioulsy, rather than discuss the facts and argue history, you would like to engage in personal attacks.  Oh well, thank you for providing me with some interesting reading.  <br>
<br>
Rodo<br>
